node.text: So eggcited for our next session 😍😍
This is so fun. I love blind tastings but suck at it. 😋

The new normal: blind wine tasting these fresh, mineral & zesty Albariño / Alvarinho between 5 friends in different households - how?! With a lot of planning, ingenuity, and one person who had to give up the blind cos she was the ‘central operations’.
•1st, we drank up mineral water in suitable sized 250ml glass bottles. I had my own various bottles from before, but the rest used Surgiva from @ewineasia (pic 2).
•2nd, determine the coordinating person so bottles & wines can be sent over to one place.
•3rd, @geribean11 carefully blinds the bottles & labels them a few hours before. Then gets a courier to dispatch an hour before our tasting.
•4th, receive chilled wine & get on Zoom for our super fun blind while gossiping about everything else.
🥂
Bonus: keeping the little bottles chilled are a breeze - Tupperware & ice on table (pic 4) takes up the space of a paperback novel 😂 
For those who are interested, I’ll put tasting notes in comments.

The battle of 3 Portuguese Alvarinho / 2 Spanish Albariño: could you first identify the country?
This white grape with its moderate aromas of lime, grapefruit, peach/nectarine, usually has a subtle bitter note (like green almond or citrus pith) and is generally made in a fresh style in Portugal, and oakier style across the border in Galicia. We easily identified E: Cepas Villas, with its denser palate & oak, but only Jackie picked correctly B: Pazo Señorans given its ‘distinctive’ aromas (ahem, we had some fun with the adjectives)
